.TH "SOVEREIGN-OSCTL-GOVERNANCE" "1" "2026-07-14" "sovereign-os 0.2.0" "sovereign-os Operator Manual"
.hy
.SH NAME
.PP
sovereign-osctl-governance - governance, documentation, and surface
contracts
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]sovereign-osctl\f[R] \f[I]command\f[R] [\f[I]subcommand\f[R]]
[\f[I]options\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Architecture questions, doctrine, documentation coverage, UX,
anti-minimization, surface maps, compliance, dashboards, and
cross-module health.
.PP
This page owns 16 top-level commands.
Ownership is defined in
\f[V]docs/man/sovereign-osctl-command-topics.json\f[R] and checked
against the real dispatcher.
\f[B]sovereign-osctl help\f[R] remains authoritative for the exact
syntax shipped by the installed version.
.SH SAFETY MODEL
.PP
Scanners and reports are generally read-only.
Snapshot/apply actions alter governance history; treat waivers as
explicit reviewed exceptions rather than a way to hide gaps.
.PP
Read-only discovery should precede mutation.
JSON output, when offered, is the stable surface for automation; human
output is intended for direct operator use.
.SH COMMON WORKFLOW
.IP "1." 3
Inspect the relevant \f[B]status\f[R], \f[B]show\f[R], \f[B]list\f[R],
\f[B]info\f[R], \f[B]plan\f[R], or \f[B]doctor\f[R] surface.
.IP "2." 3
Save machine-readable output when \f[V]--json\f[R] is available.
.IP "3." 3
Review profile, device, backend, policy, and target selection.
.IP "4." 3
Apply the smallest scoped mutation.
.IP "5." 3
Re-run health/status and inspect alerts or journal output.
.SH EXAMPLES
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
sovereign-osctl architecture-qa
sovereign-osctl doc-coverage gaps --json
sovereign-osctl surface-map coverage --json
sovereign-osctl anti-minimization-audit report --json
sovereign-osctl compliance status --json
\f[R]
.fi
